Phaedra revenged herself by committing suicide, leav- ing a written letter in which she ac- cused Hippolytus of havmgattempted her chastity. His father, Theseus, acted upon the statement. Poseidon had promised to grant any three prayers which he might addi-css to him, and Theseus now preferred one for his eon's death. As Hippolytus drove along the coast to quit Attica, his horses were scared by a sea- monster sent by Poseidon, and Hip- polytus was thrown from the chariot and mortally injured. Artemis, whom Hippolytus had worshipped, appeared to him as he was dying, and apprised Theseus of his error. Hippolytus is said to have been restored to life by Aesculapius.
